As a quick and dirty method, I have been looking at runs-scored ratios, in case anybody cares. A team that on average scores a lot more runs than its opponents is probably a better bet over an extended period. As of yesterday, Cleveland is undefeated in the post-season and has scored 2.43 runs for every opponent's run; Toronto is at .800 in the post-season and scores almost two runs per opponent's run. The Cubs, at .750, score a bit over 1.25 runs for each run scored by an opponent; LA is at .600, and actually scores fewer runs on average than its opponents, about .86.
